11
00:01:16,250 --> 00:01:17,500
Story of the Week.

12
00:01:17,500 --> 00:01:22,312
The End of OpenAI Exclusivity – and What the AGI Clause Really Meant.

13
00:01:22,312 --> 00:01:45,200
Since 2019, the partnership between Microsoft and OpenAI has been a quiet power arrangement: Microsoft pours in billions, receives exclusive cloud access in return, and – in one of the most remarkable contract clauses in corporate history – the right to automatically take over OpenAI's technologies the moment OpenAI internally declared AGI .

14
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:46,750
That clause is now gone.

15
00:01:46,750 --> 00:01:48,050
Without replacement.

16
00:01:48,050 --> 00:01:56,850
The renegotiated partnership, officially announced last week, fundamentally transforms the relationship: Microsoft loses exclusivity .

17
00:01:56,850 --> 00:02:07,525
OpenAI may now distribute its products on any cloud provider – AWS, Google Cloud, Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, or directly via its own infrastructure.

18
00:02:07,525 --> 00:02:17,187
The $13B+ investment Microsoft put into the partnership  still buys access to the technology, but no longer control over its distribution.

19
00:02:17,187 --> 00:02:19,875
The AGI clause is the real signal.

20
00:02:19,875 --> 00:02:27,750
For years it was the invisible governance problem lurking in the background: Who at OpenAI decides that AGI has been reached?

21
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:35,350
And what happens to the board, the non-profit structure, the employees – when suddenly Microsoft holds first right to everything?

22
00:02:35,350 --> 00:02:47,062
The clause structurally constrained OpenAI's strategic freedom, because every step toward genuine AGI capability simultaneously brought the "emergency exit" for Microsoft closer .

23
00:02:47,062 --> 00:02:54,962
With its removal, the question arises anew: Who now defines AGI, and with what consequences for governance and regulation?

24
00:02:54,962 --> 00:03:00,725
"OpenAI will now be able to distribute its products and models to additional cloud providers."

25
00:03:00,725 --> 00:03:11,350
The renegotiation gives OpenAI the strategic freedom it needs for a multi-cloud strategy – and removes a fundamental conflict of interest around what AGI even means.

26
00:03:11,350 --> 00:03:19,937
For Microsoft, operationally little changes: Access to OpenAI models for Azure remains, Azure stays preferred cloud partner.

27
00:03:19,937 --> 00:03:22,012
But the balance of power has shifted.

28
00:03:22,012 --> 00:03:38,962
For enterprises and developers, this means in the medium term: OpenAI products will be available on more infrastructures, price negotiations with a no-longer-exclusive provider will look different, and competition between cloud providers for OpenAI workloads can begin.

29
00:03:38,962 --> 00:03:48,337
The quiet winners: AWS and Google Cloud – both can now compete for OpenAI workloads that previously had only one infrastructure option.

30
00:03:48,337 --> 00:03:55,887
Bottom Line: Microsoft invested $13B+ and still gets preferred access – but no longer control.

31
00:03:55,887 --> 00:03:58,400
OpenAI has shed its golden handcuffs.

32
00:03:58,400 --> 00:04:04,150
The real question is whether this resolves AGI governance problems or merely relocates them.

33
00:04:04,150 --> 00:04:05,487
More Top Stories.

34
00:04:05,487 --> 00:04:10,350
Pentagon Arms Up: AI on Classified Networks – Anthropic Left Out.

35
00:04:10,350 --> 00:04:22,762
The US Department of Defense signed agreements last week with eight tech companies: Nvidia, Microsoft, AWS, Google, OpenAI, SpaceX, Reflection AI, and others .

36
00:04:22,762 --> 00:04:35,637
The goal is deploying AI on classified networks at IL-6 (Secret) and IL-7 (Top Secret) levels – the highest available security classification for cloud infrastructure.

37
00:04:35,637 --> 00:04:42,750
The Pentagon states its objective explicitly: "United States military as an AI-first fighting force" .

38
00:04:43,675 --> 00:04:46,350
Notable for who is absent: Anthropic.

39
00:04:46,350 --> 00:04:53,812
The company insisted on guardrails that would exclude use of the technology "for domestic mass surveillance and autonomous weapons" .

40
00:04:53,812 --> 00:04:56,512
The Pentagon did not accept these conditions.

41
00:04:56,512 --> 00:05:03,900
The contrast with OpenAI and Google is striking: both joined the Pentagon deals without comparable public conditions.

42
00:05:03,900 --> 00:05:17,637
Whether Anthropic's position is primarily ethical or strategic in motivation cannot be definitively assessed from the outside – in effect, it means short-term exclusion from one of the largest military AI programs in the world.

43
00:05:17,637 --> 00:05:32,437
For enterprise decision-makers and compliance teams, this is relevant: Anthropic is positioning itself with publicly communicated use restrictions, which in regulated and security-critical environments can be both a differentiator and an obstacle.

44
00:05:32,437 --> 00:05:37,637
Anthropic on Track for a $900 Billion Valuation – Before the IPO.

45
00:05:37,637 --> 00:05:45,462
Anthropic is expected to close a funding round of approximately $50B in fresh capital within two weeks .

46
00:05:45,462 --> 00:05:52,162
The targeted post-money valuation is ~$900B – and could be exceeded due to high investor demand.

47
00:05:52,162 --> 00:05:59,650
For comparison: as recently as February 2026, Anthropic was valued at $380B .

48
00:05:59,650 --> 00:06:04,450
In three months, the valuation has risen 137% .

49
00:06:04,450 --> 00:06:16,537
This would put Anthropic ahead of OpenAI, which is currently valued at $852B post-money after its own $122B round earlier in 2026 .

50
00:06:16,537 --> 00:06:21,487
The 48-hour allocation window for investors signals how hot the demand is.

51
00:06:21,487 --> 00:06:30,987
Some early 2024 investors are pausing and waiting for IPO liquidity – the round is considered the likely last before a 2026 IPO .

52
00:06:30,987 --> 00:06:44,150
The number feels abstract until you put it in context: on paper, Anthropic is worth more than BMW, Deutsche Telekom, or BASF combined, without owning any hardware or physical infrastructure.

53
00:06:44,150 --> 00:06:47,425
The capital is meant to cover massive computing costs.

54
00:06:47,425 --> 00:06:59,150
The central question for 2026 and 2027 remains whether revenue growth from API, subscriptions, and enterprise licenses can justify the valuation over the medium term.

55
00:06:59,150 --> 00:07:05,837
$700 Billion for AI Infrastructure – the Largest Investment Program in Corporate History

56
00:07:05,837 --> 00:07:14,600
Alphabet, Amazon, Meta, and Microsoft will collectively spend nearly $700B on AI infrastructure in 2026 .

57
00:07:14,600 --> 00:07:23,362
That is an increase of 71% over 2024 ($410B) – and the end of this growth curve is not in sight.

58
00:07:23,362 --> 00:07:29,100
In Q1 2026 alone, over $130B was spent combined .

59
00:07:29,100 --> 00:07:37,912
The numbers behind the numbers: Meta's Hyperion data center in Louisiana costs $27B and will house millions of GPUs .

60
00:07:37,912 --> 00:07:44,487
A single Nvidia GPU costs up to $40,000 – and demand continues to outpace supply .

61
00:07:44,487 --> 00:07:54,337
Investor reactions are mixed: Meta's stock fell after Q1 earnings despite strong AI investment, while Alphabet and Amazon rose on cloud growth.

62
00:07:54,337 --> 00:08:01,150
The paradox: the four companies are simultaneously building infrastructure for their own models and for competitors.

63
00:08:01,150 --> 00:08:10,787
AWS and Google Cloud sell compute capacity to Anthropic and OpenAI – the very companies that could potentially replace their own AI services.

64
00:08:10,787 --> 00:08:17,400
This is structurally unstable terrain, but for now infrastructure build-out buys time and market position.

65
00:08:17,400 --> 00:08:18,350
